INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1054,4503,'Mark Harmsma','mharmsma@twinfield.com','http://www.markharmsma.nl','84.106.121.73','2015-03-25 11:34:58','2015-03-25 15:34:58','Hi April, thanks for this sharing this blog. Really helps in getting overview in subjects I\'ve been more or less aware off. You have a bucket for prospect content but the text still refers to your version 2 I guess, marketing content. Cheers, Mark',0,'1','','',0,0),(1055,4503,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','74.15.3.204','2015-03-25 12:02:29','2015-03-25 16:02:29','Oh wow - good catch Mark! Thanks for pointing that out - fixed now :)',0,'1','','',0,4),(1056,4537,'Mark Evans','mark@markevans.ca','http://www.markevans.ca','174.116.246.241','2015-03-25 07:16:25','2015-03-25 11:16:25','We\'re \"X for X\" suggests a couple of things - laziness and taking short cuts when it comes to messaging. It means a startup thinks they can get away with making a comparison to a well-known commodity to tell their story, rather than investing the time to tell their own story. At best, it\'s a short-term proposition because eventually target audiences will want a unique narrative as/if they dig a little a deeper.',0,'1','','',0,0),(1057,4537,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','74.15.3.204','2015-03-25 12:01:14','2015-03-25 16:01:14','Yes, yesterday someone else made the \"lazy\" comment about this approach too. I\'m not sure if it\'s lazy as much as folks just aren\'t experienced at doing messaging and because this approach is common, they believe that it\'s the best way to do it. \nI agree with you on the short-term aspect of it but then again, messaging and positioning should constantly evolving as the market evolves so I wouldn\'t knock an approach just because you might have to change it later.',0,'1','','',0,4),(1058,4537,'Amoor Avakian','amoor@ginosi.com','http://www.ginosi.com','46.70.49.162','2015-03-26 15:09:37','2015-03-26 19:09:37','Saying that you\'re the X of Y is something we\'ve done for a long time. Only the nouns have changed, at the core it is using a metaphor to help people understand your business quickly, with all the disadvantages of a metaphor and all the misconceptions of X.\n\nI\'m not sure it\'s often because of inability to position or laziness. I think it says \"I don\'t have time to really go into this with you because I\'m spraying and praying and meeting a 1000 people a month\"\n\nIt\'s a coping mechanism for many young entrepreneurs for whom there is just too much advice, too many people, too much information, too much networking, too many events, too much irrelevance and too many things to think about at any one time.',0,'1','','',0,0),(1059,4537,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','74.15.3.204','2015-03-30 14:51:26','2015-03-30 18:51:26','Oh man Amoor - I hear you on that. In particular I think that entrepreneurs must drive themselves crazy trying to sift through all of the conflicting advice. That\'s a skill in itself. \nThe big thing to remember is that what works for other people doesn\'t necessarily work for you. If the X for Y approach is working for you, don\'t fix what isn\'t broken. But again, that\'s just my own crummy opinion - decide for yourself if it\'s one you should listen to :)',0,'1','','',0,4),(1060,4578,'Karolis','karolis@horiondigital.com','http://horiondigital.com','60.242.177.140','2015-04-01 09:36:02','2015-04-01 13:36:02','Agreed. It is. And it\'s my birthday as well.. The only problem is that I\'m serious..',0,'1','','',0,0),(1061,4578,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','74.15.3.204','2015-04-01 09:40:53','2015-04-01 13:40:53','Happy birthday! \nWell, if it makes you feel better my name is April but I wasn\'t born in April. Apparently this matters to people :)',0,'1','','',0,4),(1062,4578,'Karolis','karolis@horiondigital.com','http://horiondigital.com','60.242.177.140','2015-04-01 13:03:55','2015-04-01 17:03:55','Thank you April! \nWe\'re kinda on the same boat! I haven\'t realised that until you told me.\n\nHave a great 30 days of April!',0,'1','','',0,0),(1063,4578,'Dili','dilicfrancis@gmail.com','','76.97.42.53','2015-04-02 07:24:14','2015-04-02 11:24:14','haha - and the title had me so intrigued... well, at least it\'s not my birthday.\nHappy birthday Karolis!',0,'1','','',0,0),(1064,4578,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','74.15.3.204','2015-04-02 07:49:44','2015-04-02 11:49:44','That\'s as close to a click bait title as you are ever going to get from me :)',0,'1','','',0,4),(1065,4658,'Vinay Bhagat','vinay@trustradius.com','http://www.trustradius.com','70.112.160.78','2015-06-18 10:19:59','2015-06-18 14:19:59','April - how much trust do prospective buyers place in a buyer\'s guide written by the company vs. an objective 3rd party that covers the category more broadly?\n\nVinay\n\nVinay Bhagat\nFounder &amp; CEO, TrustRadius\n@vinaybhagat',0,'1','','',0,0),(1066,4658,'April Dunford','aprildunford@gmail.com','http://www.rocketwatcher.com','216.16.228.6','2015-06-18 10:38:29','2015-06-18 14:38:29','Hi Vinay,\nThey don\'t trust vendor content as much as they trust an objective 3rd party, but like I mention in the post, that doesn\'t mean that they won\'t consume your content too. Also for startups, in many cases there is no 3rd party covering the category so that isn\'t an option for prospects. Lastly, many B2B companies have paid for 3rd party white papers or buyer\'s guides and I have seen prospects question how objective the 3rd party really is. \nMy point is - your point of view as a vendor is relevant and prospects will consume it (in many of my startups, the Buyer\'s Guide was our most effective piece of content for generating leads), even if they do so with the full knowledge that it is written from a biased company point of view.',0,'1','','',0,4);
